🔹 Types of Joins in PySpark
Explanation

“In Apache Spark, joins are used to combine data from two DataFrames based on a common key, and different join types
determine how matching and non-matching records are handled.”

🔹 1. Inner Join
Explanation

“Returns only matching rows from both DataFrames.”

Code
df1.join(df2, "id", "inner").show()
🔹 2. Left Join (Left Outer)
Explanation

“Returns all rows from the left DataFrame and matching rows from the right; non-matching rows get nulls.”

Code
df1.join(df2, "id", "left").show()
🔹 3. Right Join (Right Outer)
Explanation

“Returns all rows from the right DataFrame and matching rows from the left.”

Code
df1.join(df2, "id", "right").show()
🔹 4. Full Outer Join
Explanation

“Returns all rows from both DataFrames, with nulls for non-matching rows.”

Code
df1.join(df2, "id", "outer").show()
🔹 5. Left Semi Join
Explanation

“Returns only rows from the left DataFrame that have a match in the right DataFrame (no columns from right).”

Code
df1.join(df2, "id", "left_semi").show()
🔹 6. Left Anti Join
Explanation

“Returns rows from the left DataFrame that do NOT have a match in the right DataFrame.”

Code
df1.join(df2, "id", "left_anti").show()
🔹 7. Cross Join
Explanation

“Returns the Cartesian product of both DataFrames (every row with every row).”

Code
df1.crossJoin(df2).show()


2) “Inner join returns only matching records, while outer joins preserve unmatched data with null values, making them useful when data completeness is required.

3) In Apache Spark, a broadcast join is an optimization technique where the smaller DataFrame is broadcasted to all executors, allowing the join to be performed locally without shuffling the larger DataFrame.
Broadcast join avoids expensive shuffle by sending the smaller dataset to all executors, enabling local joins and improving performance

4) In Apache Spark, broadcast join should be used when one of the DataFrames is small enough to fit in memory, allowing it to be distributed to all executors and avoiding expensive shuffle operations.
Broadcast join is used when one dataset is small enough to fit in memory, allowing Spark to distribute it across all executors and perform the join locally, thereby avoiding expensive shuffle operations.

5) In Apache Spark, a sort-merge join is a join strategy where both DataFrames are first partitioned and sorted on the join key, and then merged to produce the joined result efficiently.
Sort-merge join is a join strategy used when both datasets are large, where Spark shuffles and sorts both datasets on the join key and then merges them. It is scalable but expensive due to shuffle and sorting

6) In Apache Spark, a shuffle hash join is a join strategy where both DataFrames are shuffled based on the join key, and then a hash table is built on the smaller partition of one dataset to efficiently match rows from the other dataset
Shuffle hash join is a join strategy where Spark shuffles both datasets and builds a hash table on the smaller side of each partition to perform the join efficiently, avoiding sorting but requiring sufficient memory

7) In Apache Spark, join optimization involves reducing shuffle, choosing the right join strategy, and managing data distribution to improve performance and scalability
1. Use Broadcast Join (Most Important)
Explanation

Broadcast the smaller dataset to avoid shuffle on the larger dataset.

Code
from pyspark.sql.functions import broadcast

df_large.join(broadcast(df_small), "id").show()
Why it matters

Avoids expensive shuffle → fastest join strategy.

🔹 2. Filter Data Before Join
Explanation

Reduce dataset size before joining.

Code
df1_filtered = df1.filter("amount > 1000")
df1_filtered.join(df2, "id").show()
Why it matters

Less data → less shuffle → faster execution.

🔹 3. Select Only Required Columns
Explanation

Avoid unnecessary data transfer.

Code
df1.select("id", "amount").join(df2.select("id", "name"), "id").show()
Why it matters

Reduces memory and network usage.

🔹 4. Use Proper Join Type
Explanation

Use left_semi or left_anti when possible instead of full joins.

Code
df1.join(df2, "id", "left_semi").show()
Why it matters

Processes less data → faster.

🔹 5. Repartition Data on Join Key
Explanation

Align partitions to reduce shuffle overhead.

Code
df1 = df1.repartition("id")
df2 = df2.repartition("id")

df1.join(df2, "id").show()
Why it matters

Improves data locality and reduces shuffle cost.

🔹 6. Handle Data Skew
Explanation

Avoid uneven data distribution.

Code (salting example)
from pyspark.sql.functions import rand, floor

df1 = df1.withColumn("salt", floor(rand()*10))
df2 = df2.withColumn("salt", floor(rand()*10))

df1.join(df2, ["id", "salt"]).show()
Why it matters

Prevents one executor from becoming a bottleneck.

🔹 7. Tune Shuffle Partitions
Explanation

Adjust number of partitions.

Code
spark.conf.set("spark.sql.shuffle.partitions", "100")
Why it matters

Too many → overhead
Too few → slow parallelism

🔹 8. Avoid Cross Join
Explanation

Cross join produces Cartesian product.

Code
# Avoid unless necessary
df1.crossJoin(df2)
Why it matters

Explodes data → huge performance impact.

⚡ Key Insight

👉
“Join performance in Spark is primarily affected by shuffle, so minimizing shuffle is the most important optimization strategy.”
