8 & 9) In Apache Spark, skewed data refers to an uneven distribution of data across partitions, where a few keys or partitions contain a disproportionately large amount of data, leading to performance bottlenecks.
How to Handle Skew
🔹 1. Salting (Most common)
from pyspark.sql.functions import rand, floor

df1 = df1.withColumn("salt", floor(rand()*10))
df2 = df2.withColumn("salt", floor(rand()*10))

df1.join(df2, ["key", "salt"]).show()
🔹 2. Broadcast Join

👉 If one side is small

from pyspark.sql.functions import broadcast

df_large.join(broadcast(df_small), "key").show()
🔹 3. Repartition
df = df.repartition("key")
🔹 4. Use AQE (Adaptive Query Execution)
spark.conf.set("spark.sql.adaptive.enabled", "true")
⚡ Key Insight

👉
“Skew causes uneven workload distribution, making one executor a bottleneck while others remain idle.”

🎤 Strong Interview Answer

👉
“Data skew occurs when data is unevenly distributed across partitions, causing some tasks to process significantly more data than others, leading to performance bottlenecks. It can be handled using techniques like salting, broadcasting small tables, and repartitioning.”

